---
title: Resolvers
description: Resolvers fulfill requirements raised by constraints. They fetch data, perform async operations, and update facts to satisfy the system.
---

Resolvers are how requirements get fulfilled - they do the actual work. {% .lead %}

---

## Basic Resolvers

Define resolvers in your module:

```typescript
const userModule = createModule("user", {
  schema: {
    facts: {
      userId: t.number(),
      user: t.object<User>().nullable(),
    },
    requirements: {
      FETCH_USER: t.object<{ userId: number }>(),
    },
  },

  resolvers: {
    fetchUser: {
      requirement: "FETCH_USER",
      resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
        const user = await api.getUser(req.userId);
        ctx.facts.user = user;
      },
    },
  },
});
```

---

## Anatomy of a Resolver

```typescript
resolvers: {
  resolverName: {
    // Which requirement this handles
    requirement: "REQUIREMENT_TYPE",

    // Custom identity key (optional)
    key: (req) => `fetch-${req.userId}`,

    // Retry configuration (optional)
    retry: { attempts: 3, backoff: "exponential" },

    // Timeout in milliseconds (optional)
    timeout: 5000,

    // Batch similar requirements (optional)
    batch: { maxSize: 10, debounceMs: 50 },

    // The resolver function
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Fulfill the requirement
    },
  },
}
```

---

## The `resolve` Function

Resolvers receive the requirement and a context object:

```typescript
resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
  // req: The requirement object with type and payload
  // ctx: Context with facts, derivations, and helpers

  const data = await fetchData(req.id);
  ctx.facts.data = data;
}
```

### Context Object

```typescript
resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
  // Access facts
  const userId = ctx.facts.userId;

  // Access derivations
  const isAdmin = ctx.derive.isAdmin;

  // Update facts
  ctx.facts.user = await api.getUser(userId);

  // Dispatch events
  ctx.dispatch("USER_LOADED", { userId });

  // Batch updates
  ctx.batch(() => {
    ctx.facts.loading = false;
    ctx.facts.error = null;
  });
}
```

---

## Matching Requirements

### By Type

The simplest matching - by requirement type:

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchUser: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Handles all FETCH_USER requirements
    },
  },
}
```

### By Function

Match with a function for complex logic:

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchData: {
    handles: (req) => req.type.startsWith("FETCH_"),
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Handles FETCH_USER, FETCH_PROFILE, FETCH_SETTINGS, etc.
    },
  },
}
```

---

## Requirement Identity

### Default Identity

By default, requirements are deduplicated by their entire payload:

```typescript
// These are the same requirement (deduplicated)
require: { type: "FETCH_USER", userId: 123 }
require: { type: "FETCH_USER", userId: 123 }

// These are different requirements (both run)
require: { type: "FETCH_USER", userId: 123 }
require: { type: "FETCH_USER", userId: 456 }
```

### Custom Keys

Use custom keys for fine-grained control:

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchUser: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    key: (req) => `user-${req.userId}`,
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Only one fetch per userId at a time
    },
  },
}
```

---

## Retry Policies

Configure automatic retries:

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchData: {
    requirement: "FETCH_DATA",
    retry: {
      attempts: 3,          // Max retry attempts
      backoff: "exponential", // "fixed" | "linear" | "exponential"
      initialDelay: 100,    // First retry delay (ms)
      maxDelay: 5000,       // Max delay between retries
    },
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Will retry on failure
    },
  },
}
```

### Backoff Strategies

| Strategy | Pattern |
|----------|---------|
| `fixed` | Same delay every time (e.g., 100, 100, 100) |
| `linear` | Increasing by initial (e.g., 100, 200, 300) |
| `exponential` | Doubles each time (e.g., 100, 200, 400) |

### Conditional Retry

```typescript
retry: {
  attempts: 3,
  shouldRetry: (error, attempt) => {
    // Don't retry 4xx errors
    if (error.status >= 400 && error.status < 500) {
      return false;
    }
    return attempt < 3;
  },
}
```

---

## Timeouts

Set maximum execution time:

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchData: {
    requirement: "FETCH_DATA",
    timeout: 5000, // 5 seconds
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Aborts if takes longer than 5s
    },
  },
}
```

### Timeout Handling

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchData: {
    requirement: "FETCH_DATA",
    timeout: 5000,
    onTimeout: (req, ctx) => {
      ctx.facts.error = "Request timed out";
      ctx.facts.loading = false;
    },
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // ...
    },
  },
}
```

---

## Batching

Group similar requirements together:

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchUsers: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    batch: {
      maxSize: 10,      // Max items per batch
      debounceMs: 50,   // Wait time to collect more
    },
    resolve: async (requirements, ctx) => {
      // requirements is an array when batching
      const userIds = requirements.map(r => r.userId);
      const users = await api.getUsers(userIds);

      // Update facts for each
      users.forEach(user => {
        ctx.facts.usersById[user.id] = user;
      });
    },
  },
}
```

### When to Batch

- Fetching multiple similar resources
- Avoiding N+1 problems
- API supports batch endpoints

---

## Error Handling

### In Resolvers

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchUser: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      try {
        ctx.facts.user = await api.getUser(req.userId);
      } catch (error) {
        ctx.facts.error = error.message;
        ctx.facts.user = null;
      }
    },
  },
}
```

### Error Handler

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchUser: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    onError: (error, req, ctx) => {
      ctx.facts.error = error.message;
      ctx.dispatch("ERROR", { type: "FETCH_FAILED", error });
    },
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      ctx.facts.user = await api.getUser(req.userId);
    },
  },
}
```

---

## Parallel vs Sequential

### Parallel (Default)

Independent requirements resolve in parallel:

```typescript
// These run in parallel
constraints: {
  fetchUser: {
    when: (facts) => !facts.user,
    require: { type: "FETCH_USER" },
  },
  fetchSettings: {
    when: (facts) => !facts.settings,
    require: { type: "FETCH_SETTINGS" },
  },
}
```

### Sequential

Use constraint ordering for sequential resolution:

```typescript
constraints: {
  fetchUser: {
    when: (facts) => !facts.user,
    require: { type: "FETCH_USER" },
  },
  fetchProfile: {
    after: ["fetchUser"],
    when: (facts) => facts.user && !facts.profile,
    require: { type: "FETCH_PROFILE", userId: (facts) => facts.user.id },
  },
}
```

---

## Common Patterns

### Loading States

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchUser: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      ctx.facts.loading = true;
      try {
        ctx.facts.user = await api.getUser(req.userId);
        ctx.facts.error = null;
      } catch (error) {
        ctx.facts.error = error.message;
      } finally {
        ctx.facts.loading = false;
      }
    },
  },
}
```

### Optimistic Updates

```typescript
resolvers: {
  updateUser: {
    requirement: "UPDATE_USER",
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Save original for rollback
      const original = ctx.facts.user;

      // Optimistic update
      ctx.facts.user = { ...original, ...req.updates };

      try {
        ctx.facts.user = await api.updateUser(req.userId, req.updates);
      } catch (error) {
        // Rollback on failure
        ctx.facts.user = original;
        ctx.facts.error = error.message;
      }
    },
  },
}
```

### Cache-First

```typescript
resolvers: {
  fetchData: {
    requirement: "FETCH_DATA",
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      // Check cache first
      const cached = ctx.facts.cache[req.id];
      if (cached && !isStale(cached)) {
        return; // Use cached data
      }

      // Fetch fresh
      const data = await api.getData(req.id);
      ctx.facts.data = data;
      ctx.facts.cache[req.id] = { data, fetchedAt: Date.now() };
    },
  },
}
```

---

## TypeScript Integration

Requirements and resolvers are fully typed:

```typescript
schema: {
  requirements: {
    FETCH_USER: t.object<{ userId: number; includeProfile?: boolean }>(),
  },
}

resolvers: {
  fetchUser: {
    requirement: "FETCH_USER",
    resolve: async (req, ctx) => {
      req.userId;         // number
      req.includeProfile; // boolean | undefined
    },
  },
}
```

